00:04:50.740 --> 00:04:54.260
Because he invented it all.

00:04:54.260 --> 00:04:58.230
It is amazing this guy, how
he, he comes, he comes from it

00:04:58.230 --> 00:05:02.340
from a performers perspective,
from an intellectual perspective,

00:05:02.340 --> 00:05:07.260
from a sound perspective
and from a game almost kind

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:10.100
of like improvising perspective.

00:05:10.100 --> 00:05:12.370
And you see that in the score.

00:05:12.370 --> 00:05:16.290
So did you want to say a
little bit about the score?

00:05:16.290 --> 00:05:17.590
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Choi: Sure.

00:05:17.590 --> 00:05:21.130
So this is his composition
number 222.

00:05:21.130 --> 00:05:25.980
And he, he wrote this in 1995.

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:28.890
And it was, it was after
he was, he went to a course

00:05:28.890 --> 00:05:30.830
on Native American music.

00:05:30.830 --> 00:05:36.790
So he called it the Ghost Trance
Music -- this particular piece.

00:05:36.790 --> 00:05:42.240
And he was really interested in
the ritual dance music and music

00:05:42.240 --> 00:05:44.490
for other purposes than
just in the concert hall.

00:05:44.490 --> 00:05:45.890
So he is going for that.

00:05:45.890 --> 00:05:49.030
And then there is specific
symbols, like circles and triangles

00:05:49.030 --> 00:05:51.140
and squares that come
out of a note head.

00:05:51.140 --> 00:05:53.570
And that is where we are
supposed to start improvising.

00:05:53.570 --> 00:05:57.440
And then we have to find each other
also in the score out of that.

00:05:57.440 --> 00:05:59.080
And come back to the Ghost Trance.

00:05:59.080 --> 00:06:02.660
So the piece actually could
go on for about 24 hours.

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:04.960
We have to do it today
in like 10 minutes

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:07.120
or something like that [laughter].

00:06:07.120 --> 00:06:08.630
But that is what he wants.

00:06:08.630 --> 00:06:10.200
He wants you to.

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:11.880
You do not have to play all 30.

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:13.410
There is 30 pages or 33.

00:06:13.410 --> 00:06:14.760
I forget how many pages now.

00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:16.060
Yeah there is 33.

00:06:16.060 --> 00:06:17.360
There is no way we could do all 33.

00:06:17.360 --> 00:06:18.660
He does not expect you to.

00:06:18.660 --> 00:06:20.170
But you do have to
make some choices.

00:06:20.170 --> 00:06:23.070
And that can be either
very, very difficult or.

00:06:23.070 --> 00:06:27.240
I actually think that is
difficult to make these choices

00:06:27.240 --> 00:06:28.540
with the material that is given.

00:06:28.540 --> 00:06:30.140
But that is what we had to do.

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:31.440
&gt;&gt; Richard Carrick: Yeah.

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:34.370
And one of the things he does
is he sets up many paradigms.

00:06:34.370 --> 00:06:36.490
So you can, you can pick and choice

00:06:36.490 --> 00:06:38.490
at different points
what you want to do.

00:06:38.490 --> 00:06:41.530
But you do not know what the
other person is going to do.

00:06:41.530 --> 00:06:45.860
And for example, there is a
symbol, which is a circle.

00:06:45.860 --> 00:06:47.610
He might attach it to a note.

00:06:47.610 --> 00:06:50.360
But then there is also a
symbol, which is a triangle.

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:52.210
And there is a symbol
that is a square.

00:06:52.210 --> 00:06:55.040 position:56%
They all look pretty similar, right?

00:06:55.040 --> 00:06:59.030
But the circle means you improvise.

00:06:59.030 --> 00:07:05.380
The triangle means you stop playing
that piece and you immediately go

00:07:05.380 --> 00:07:10.360
to another piece that he has
written in composition 222.

00:07:10.360 --> 00:07:14.490
And the square means you
can stop playing that piece

00:07:14.490 --> 00:07:19.010
and immediately play any other
piece he has written [laughter].

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:25.380
So it is pretty open.

00:07:25.380 --> 00:07:29.950
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Choi: And actually
in the case there is a score

00:07:29.950 --> 00:07:31.260
of the tertiary material.

00:07:31.260 --> 00:07:33.690
It is numbered one,
two, three and four.

00:07:33.690 --> 00:07:37.270
So those are more specific
and he wants you to go

00:07:37.270 --> 00:07:40.230
through them like note by note.

00:07:40.230 --> 00:07:42.100
So we do. We chose.

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:44.970
I will just give you the secret in.

00:07:44.970 --> 00:07:46.790
But we chose two of
them to play tonight.

00:07:46.790 --> 00:07:48.280
Not all four.

00:07:48.280 --> 00:07:49.580
You can guess which two.

00:07:49.580 --> 00:07:53.570
But they are all displayed there
in the cabinet, which is nice.

00:07:53.570 --> 00:07:56.140
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: So if you
can go to these other pieces,

00:07:56.140 --> 00:07:58.880
does he do anything special
with the clefs or something?

00:07:58.880 --> 00:08:02.500
Or can you just pick any
line from those pieces?

00:08:02.500 --> 00:08:03.800
Or?

00:08:03.800 --> 00:08:05.100
&gt;&gt; Richard Carrick: Yeah.

00:08:05.100 --> 00:08:06.400
He. He believes that all
of his music can be played

00:08:06.400 --> 00:08:08.630
on all instruments at any time.

00:08:08.630 --> 00:08:11.650
So he has got this really
interesting synthesis.

00:08:11.650 --> 00:08:14.610
Braxton comes from many
traditions you know.

00:08:14.610 --> 00:08:18.310
Some of you are probably thinking
oh this relates to Cage in a way.

00:08:18.310 --> 00:08:21.270
The improvisation thing might
come out of a jazz tradition.

00:08:21.270 --> 00:08:24.480
Stockhausen was a big
influence on him.

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:26.590
And he cites that in
a number of examples.

00:08:26.590 --> 00:08:31.460
So he is really going deeper with
a lot of these ideas that were

00:08:31.460 --> 00:08:32.760
around when he was performing.

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:34.160
He is an incredible musician.

00:08:34.160 --> 00:08:37.880
And, and he would just kind

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:40.210
of put them all together
in this unique way.

00:08:40.210 --> 00:08:44.600
So how do you notate for
any instrument at any time.

00:08:44.600 --> 00:08:49.520
So you still use the five line
staff, but he uses his own clef.

00:08:49.520 --> 00:08:52.480
And you can do it in treble clef.

00:08:52.480 --> 00:08:53.780
You can do it in base clef.

00:08:53.780 --> 00:08:56.040
You can do it in treble clef
three octaves higher or lower.

00:08:56.040 --> 00:08:57.340
You can do it in alto clef.

00:08:57.340 --> 00:09:01.810
You can switch from one note to
tenor to soprano to alto clef.

00:09:01.810 --> 00:09:04.230
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Choi: And that
is called the diamond clef.

00:09:04.230 --> 00:09:06.380 position:56%
And you will see the diamond, right?

00:09:06.380 --> 00:09:08.160
&gt;&gt; Richard Carrick: And he also
does that with accidentals.

00:09:08.160 --> 00:09:10.450
He has a star accidental.

00:09:10.450 --> 00:09:11.750
It could be a flat.

00:09:11.750 --> 00:09:13.050
It could be a natural.

00:09:13.050 --> 00:09:14.350
It could be a sharp.

00:09:14.350 --> 00:09:17.430
And we do not know what
each other are going to do.

00:09:17.430 --> 00:09:18.730
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Do you find

00:09:18.730 --> 00:09:20.650
that you play it differently
as you are doing it?

00:09:20.650 --> 00:09:25.910
Or do you, do some mapping
and some spontaneous choices?

00:09:25.910 --> 00:09:27.210
Or?

00:09:27.210 --> 00:09:30.150
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Choi: Yes
and no [laughter].

00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:32.490
Because either way can
be frustrating, right?

00:09:32.490 --> 00:09:34.310
So you are trying to play
everything on the page

00:09:34.310 --> 00:09:36.770
and that almost got more
