00:15:49.800 --> 00:15:51.100
[Inaudible].

00:15:51.100 --> 00:15:53.140
&gt;&gt; Richard Carrick: Starting off
by saying something about Spur.

00:15:53.140 --> 00:16:00.750 position:56%
Spur is a piece where the piano part
is rapid 30 second notes throughout.

00:16:00.750 --> 00:16:05.460
And the string quartet are also
kind of this dual personality.

00:16:05.460 --> 00:16:07.060
They are completely integrated,

00:16:07.060 --> 00:16:09.980
but they almost never
play exactly the same.

00:16:09.980 --> 00:16:11.280
It is. It is.

00:16:11.280 --> 00:16:12.690
It is incredibly difficult.

00:16:12.690 --> 00:16:15.780
Because you know normally
you have downbeats together

00:16:15.780 --> 00:16:17.080
or something like that.

00:16:17.080 --> 00:16:19.160
And he does not do
that in this piece.

00:16:19.160 --> 00:16:23.960
So it is kind of a meta-listening,
I think is happening here.

00:16:23.960 --> 00:16:25.260
&gt;&gt; Taka Kigawa: Yeah.

00:16:25.260 --> 00:16:27.780
It is also interesting to know
that he put specific [inaudible]

00:16:27.780 --> 00:16:30.470
for piano and the string quartet.

00:16:30.470 --> 00:16:33.860
He did not put for piano quintet.

00:16:33.860 --> 00:16:37.340
So piano and string
quartet playing together.

00:16:37.340 --> 00:16:41.860
But I always feel like when
the performers are rehearsing,

00:16:41.860 --> 00:16:43.160
where am I?

00:16:43.160 --> 00:16:44.530 position:56%
Am I playing with the string quartet

00:16:44.530 --> 00:16:49.590
or very string quartet those
four boys and girls playing here?

00:16:49.590 --> 00:16:51.800
But I am like here.

00:16:51.800 --> 00:16:55.170
We are together, but at
the same time not together.

00:16:55.170 --> 00:16:58.420
Very peculiar experience anytime.

00:16:58.420 --> 00:17:02.300
Yeah. Sometimes I feel like when
discussing string [inaudible]

00:17:02.300 --> 00:17:06.710
discussing phrasing or [inaudible],
I feel like I am nowhere.

00:17:06.710 --> 00:17:08.270
I feel so helpless.

00:17:08.270 --> 00:17:11.700
But at the same time, we
are really playing together.

00:17:11.700 --> 00:17:13.670
So very strange feeling.

00:17:13.670 --> 00:17:16.250
&gt;&gt; Richard Carrick: So if you were
off, it would definitely feel off.

00:17:16.250 --> 00:17:18.200
So it [inaudible] where
you have to be exactly

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:19.960
on for it to feel correctly off.

00:17:19.960 --> 00:17:21.660
&gt;&gt; Taka Kigawa: Exactly [laughter].

00:17:21.660 --> 00:17:23.240
Very, very right.

00:17:23.240 --> 00:17:25.930
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Choi: And I think
that is, that is how he works.

00:17:25.930 --> 00:17:29.760
We had. Each of us has
had a opportunity to work

00:17:29.760 --> 00:17:31.380
with him on a different level.

00:17:31.380 --> 00:17:35.400
And when he came to New York City,
I was doing a large ensemble piece.

00:17:35.400 --> 00:17:37.820
So we had pretty much
a full orchestra.

00:17:37.820 --> 00:17:42.650
And he was so specific about
every dynamic that he wants.

00:17:42.650 --> 00:17:43.950
Every nuance.

00:17:43.950 --> 00:17:45.660
Every extended technique.

00:17:45.660 --> 00:17:47.540
And I was sitting, I
think, somewhere in the back

00:17:47.540 --> 00:17:49.230
of the first violin somewhere.

00:17:49.230 --> 00:17:50.530
The very back.

00:17:50.530 --> 00:17:52.820
And he is listening from
kind of inside the orchestra.

00:17:52.820 --> 00:17:54.820
And he said, okay everybody stop.

00:17:54.820 --> 00:17:58.300 position:56%
And he pointed me out and he said,
you are playing too loud [laughter].

00:17:58.300 --> 00:18:01.630
It was like well everything
was supposed to be PP

00:18:01.630 --> 00:18:02.930
or PPP or PPPP, whatever.

00:18:02.930 --> 00:18:05.330
But he could hear that.

00:18:05.330 --> 00:18:09.460
So that is the extent of
how meticulously he writes.

00:18:09.460 --> 00:18:12.940 position:56%
Now you might listen to it and
think oh well you know this could be

00:18:12.940 --> 00:18:14.240
like an improvised thing.

00:18:14.240 --> 00:18:15.540
We have a lot of Pizzicato's

00:18:15.540 --> 00:18:17.500
and like you know somebody
plays here and then here.

00:18:17.500 --> 00:18:19.150
It is like doot, doot,
doot, like that.

00:18:19.150 --> 00:18:20.450
But it is not.

00:18:20.450 --> 00:18:23.960
It is like you have to
really have it in your body.

00:18:23.960 --> 00:18:25.260
The rhythm in your body.

00:18:25.260 --> 00:18:27.510
So for that piece for sure.

00:18:27.510 --> 00:18:29.350 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Richard Carrick: You know another
interesting thing about this piece

00:18:29.350 --> 00:18:33.640
that I was mentioning to Taka
earlier that in a lot of, of,

00:18:33.640 --> 00:18:37.460
for his piano music, he tends
to do these kind of octave,

00:18:37.460 --> 00:18:41.320
splaying octaves that go across
the compass of the keyboard.

00:18:41.320 --> 00:18:44.050
But also in, almost intentional,

00:18:44.050 --> 00:18:46.190
well obviously intentional
because he writes it.

00:18:46.190 --> 00:18:48.560
But not wrong notes.

00:18:48.560 --> 00:18:53.170
But kind of moving away from
some sort of octave center.

00:18:53.170 --> 00:18:55.470
So in this case, it
might be a minor ninth,

00:18:55.470 --> 00:18:57.260
it might be a major
seventh somewhere.

00:18:57.260 --> 00:18:59.840
But there is this kind of gradual
type of thing that always tends

00:18:59.840 --> 00:19:02.350
to snap back until finally
it shifts or something.

00:19:02.350 --> 00:19:06.210 position:56%
And it is kind of this amazing thing
to listen to over time, I think.

00:19:06.210 --> 00:19:07.510
And it is.

00:19:07.510 --> 00:19:13.590
So I am really excited about it.

00:19:13.590 --> 00:19:16.120
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: How
would you categorize.

00:19:16.120 --> 00:19:17.420
Or not categorize.

00:19:17.420 --> 00:19:22.600
But think about the clarinet
quintet compared to that piece?

00:19:22.600 --> 00:19:23.900
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Choi: Okay.

00:19:23.900 --> 00:19:27.310
So in the clarinet quintet,
which was written in 2013,

00:19:27.310 --> 00:19:30.140
he is exploring something
completely different.

00:19:30.140 --> 00:19:33.580
So he is. He wants to stretch
time, especially in the beginning.

00:19:33.580 --> 00:19:34.880
He wants the whole.

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:37.190
The whole piece is around
30 minutes actually.

00:19:37.190 --> 00:19:40.100
In the first 15 minutes,
that is half of the piece,

00:19:40.100 --> 00:19:45.550
he is trying to do
everything in slow motion.

00:19:45.550 --> 00:19:46.850
That is the whole point.

00:19:46.850 --> 00:19:49.950
And Interno al Bianco [assumed
spelling] is, it is a reference

00:19:49.950 --> 00:19:51.470
to a piece of literature actually.

00:19:51.470 --> 00:19:52.920
An Italian piece.

00:19:52.920 --> 00:19:56.600
And actually he says it does not
have to do with the actual title.

00:19:56.600 --> 00:20:02.960
But he is exploring light
and all sense of light.

00:20:02.960 --> 00:20:07.380
But you have to imagine in all the
colors and all the distinctions.

00:20:07.380 --> 00:20:10.590
And he is trying to make.

00:20:10.590 --> 00:20:12.490
If light were to sound
like something,

00:20:12.490 --> 00:20:15.020
this is what it would sound like.

00:20:15.020 --> 00:20:20.910
So we are supposed to try to find
this place in our string playing

00:20:20.910 --> 00:20:23.060
and also in the clarinet
where we blend.

00:20:23.060 --> 00:20:25.880
But it is a certain sound that
maybe you have not heard before.

00:20:25.880 --> 00:20:28.050
And he just stays there
for 15 minutes.

00:20:28.050 --> 00:20:29.420
That is, that is a big deal.

00:20:29.420 --> 00:20:30.970 position:56%
And then the piece starts to evolve.

00:20:30.970 --> 00:20:34.600
I do not want to give
everything away [laughter].

00:20:34.600 --> 00:20:36.820
&gt;&gt; Richard Carrick: But one
of the fascinating things

00:20:36.820 --> 00:20:40.260
about that piece -- I, I
hear the piece, I think,

00:20:40.260 --> 00:20:42.420
I think he wrote it
last year actually.

00:20:42.420 --> 00:20:43.720
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Choi: Oh is that right?

00:20:43.720 --> 00:20:45.020
&gt;&gt; Richard Carrick: Because it
was just premiered in September

00:20:45.020 --> 00:20:46.320
and then we premiered in...

00:20:46.320 --> 00:20:47.620
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Choi: Sorry 2015.

00:20:47.620 --> 00:20:49.010
&gt;&gt; Richard Carrick: In the U.S.
a few weeks ago in New York.

00:20:49.010 --> 00:20:51.770
And this is the, as you
said, the D.C. premier.

00:20:51.770 --> 00:20:55.340
And I think it is a
new phase in his music.

00:20:55.340 --> 00:21:00.730
You heard the last few
pieces from 2013 to 16,

00:21:00.730 --> 00:21:03.340
there is a change going
on in his music.

00:21:03.340 --> 00:21:05.980
And in this piece it
is pretty full blown.

00:21:05.980 --> 00:21:12.400
One of the things that happens
is acoustics become so important.

00:21:12.400 --> 00:21:15.960
In the way that in Spur it is all
about these little motives, bop,

00:21:15.960 --> 00:21:18.740
bop, bop, bop, bad da
da, bad da da, you know.

00:21:18.740 --> 00:21:23.140
This kind of phrenetic
micro-intensity throughout the

00:21:23.140 --> 00:21:24.600
whole piece.

00:21:24.600 --> 00:21:30.030
But in Interno, the piece really
opens up and the acoustics

00:21:30.030 --> 00:21:33.200
and the sounds of the instruments,
the way they are interacting

00:21:33.200 --> 00:21:36.780
with each other sonically
is phenomenal.

00:21:36.780 --> 00:21:41.110
It takes such concentration
to kind of play these pieces.

00:21:41.110 --> 00:21:45.400
And there is also something about
how long the piece is you know.

00:21:45.400 --> 00:21:47.930
We tend to hear.

00:21:47.930 --> 00:21:52.260
It is a funny thing, like do you
think you would hear the same.

00:21:52.260 --> 00:21:56.200
Let's say we took the first
30 seconds of a piece.

00:21:56.200 --> 00:21:58.610
I have never tried this before.

00:21:58.610 --> 00:22:01.250
But let's say you take the
first 30 seconds of a piece

00:22:01.250 --> 00:22:03.990
and then you hear it at
the beginning of the piece.

00:22:03.990 --> 00:22:05.570
It means something.

00:22:05.570 --> 00:22:09.990
But if you heard that same
30 seconds three minutes

00:22:09.990 --> 00:22:13.870
into the piece, it might
mean something else depending

00:22:13.870 --> 00:22:15.170
on what came before.

00:22:15.170 --> 00:22:18.530
If you take the first 30 seconds
and you hear it 15 minutes

00:22:18.530 --> 00:22:23.040
into the piece, you could
imagine how that same piece

00:22:23.040 --> 00:22:26.930
of music would have a different
meaning because of its context.

00:22:26.930 --> 00:22:30.510
And I think what he does in
this piece is he stretches

00:22:30.510 --> 00:22:35.770
out the scale a little bit to the
point where we really get lost

00:22:35.770 --> 00:22:38.610
in this slow expansive music.

00:22:38.610 --> 00:22:41.470
We are no longer just
waiting for it to get fast.

00:22:41.470 --> 00:22:43.580
It is. That is where we are.

00:22:43.580 --> 00:22:45.870
And we start to hear the music
differently for that reason.

00:22:45.870 --> 00:22:49.040
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: You know another
