00:37:20.330 --> 00:37:21.730
Surely somebody has a question.

00:37:21.730 --> 00:37:24.030
There we go.

00:37:37.040 --> 00:37:38.720
&gt;&gt; So I cannot wait
to hear the Braxton.

00:37:38.720 --> 00:37:44.610
The way you described
the improvisation

00:37:44.610 --> 00:37:46.500
and the jumping around
and everything.

00:37:46.500 --> 00:37:48.670
Is he unique as a composer
in doing that?

00:37:48.670 --> 00:37:51.510
Or do, have other composers
done that as well?

00:37:51.510 --> 00:37:53.500
&gt;&gt; Richard Carrick:
That is a good question.

00:37:53.500 --> 00:37:54.800
Composers have done that.

00:37:54.800 --> 00:37:56.100
And improvisation.

00:37:56.100 --> 00:38:00.100
You know if you go back
in history, improvisation

00:38:00.100 --> 00:38:03.960
and composition were
almost the same act.

00:38:03.960 --> 00:38:05.700
I mean very often the composer

00:38:05.700 --> 00:38:11.100 position:56%
in Mozart's time improvise a piece
you know based on these formal rules

00:38:11.100 --> 00:38:17.010
and so forth and kind
of deviated from them.

00:38:17.010 --> 00:38:20.950
So improvisation and composition
have always been linked.

00:38:20.950 --> 00:38:26.270
It is true that since the, since
modern times, you know certainly

00:38:26.270 --> 00:38:30.840
in the last hundred years
improvisation has kind

00:38:30.840 --> 00:38:35.430
of been weeded out of
a lot of notated music.

00:38:35.430 --> 00:38:40.670
But Anthony Braxton does it
in a very unique way I think.

00:38:40.670 --> 00:38:44.140
He really wants to setup
this trance you know.

00:38:44.140 --> 00:38:48.720 position:56%
And that is like, that is one of
the great tricks of this piece is --

00:38:48.720 --> 00:38:51.210
how do you both be in a trance
and constantly changing.

00:38:51.210 --> 00:38:53.990
You know, you cannot do both.

00:38:53.990 --> 00:38:55.420
So. So how do you kind
of deal with that?

00:38:55.420 --> 00:39:00.260
As a performer what choices do you
make and when do you make them?

00:39:00.260 --> 00:39:02.170
But there are many
others who do that.

00:39:02.170 --> 00:39:05.180
And as Jennifer said, he is
part of the AACM and many

00:39:05.180 --> 00:39:08.220
of those composers, Muhal
Richard Abrams, George Lewis

00:39:08.220 --> 00:39:17.980
and many others have been dealing
with a lot of these issues.

00:39:17.980 --> 00:39:22.930
And it is not really just
notation improvisation.

00:39:22.930 --> 00:39:26.940
It is actually like how do you
find new ways of making music

00:39:26.940 --> 00:39:29.600
with performers, with
scores and so forth.

00:39:29.600 --> 00:39:31.780 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Choi: Oh the Association
of Advancement Creative Musicians.

00:39:31.780 --> 00:39:33.640
So. And they were based
out of Chicago.

00:39:33.640 --> 00:39:40.620 position:56%
And actually to answer your question
further, I had the opportunity

00:39:40.620 --> 00:39:44.860
to work with four of these
amazing founding musicians.

00:39:44.860 --> 00:39:46.480
So Wadada Leo Smith on the trumpet.

00:39:46.480 --> 00:39:47.780
Leroy Jenkins.

00:39:47.780 --> 00:39:49.080
George Lewis.

00:39:49.080 --> 00:39:50.380
And Anthony Braxton.

00:39:50.380 --> 00:39:51.680 position:56%
And having seen all of their scores,

00:39:51.680 --> 00:39:54.820
it is just so amazing how
unique each one of them.

00:39:54.820 --> 00:39:57.760
They come from the same generation.

00:39:57.760 --> 00:40:00.880
Chicago 1960's.

00:40:00.880 --> 00:40:02.180
This is when they formed.

00:40:02.180 --> 00:40:03.590
And they really wanted to.

00:40:03.590 --> 00:40:07.300 position:56%
They did not want to play just jazz.

00:40:07.300 --> 00:40:12.000
In fact, some of them did not
even have formal jazz training.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:13.710
Not all of them did.

00:40:13.710 --> 00:40:17.010
So. So it is amazing
that each of them came

00:40:17.010 --> 00:40:21.620 position:56%
up with completely different systems
of doing so, of how to do this sort

00:40:21.620 --> 00:40:25.020
of quasi structured
improve notated pieces.

00:40:25.020 --> 00:40:26.320
Very distinct.

00:40:26.320 --> 00:40:27.620
Very interesting.

00:40:27.620 --> 00:40:30.300
But also calling for the musician
to definitely improvise and go out

00:40:30.300 --> 00:40:31.640
and explore their own world.

00:40:31.640 --> 00:40:33.110
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: One thing I would
mention too, if you are interested,

00:40:33.110 --> 00:40:34.760
that George Lewis actually two
years ago wrote a biography kind

00:40:34.760 --> 00:40:36.060
of the organization.

00:40:36.060 --> 00:40:37.360
It is quite big.

00:40:37.360 --> 00:40:38.660
So you can check that
out [inaudible].

00:40:38.660 --> 00:40:39.960
&gt;&gt; Richard Carrick: It is called
A Power Stronger Than Itself.

00:40:39.960 --> 00:40:41.260 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Choi: It is fascinating.

00:40:41.260 --> 00:40:42.560
Yeah.

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:44.200
&gt;&gt; Since we are in the Library
and you have so many treasures,

00:40:44.200 --> 00:40:47.890
I was very interested in what
you said about the difference

00:40:47.890 --> 00:40:51.430
between working on the
original manuscripts core,

00:40:51.430 --> 00:40:55.700
manuscript and the final product.

00:40:55.700 --> 00:40:58.370
I am sure all of us are aware

00:40:58.370 --> 00:41:02.880
that the original manuscripts
core is disappearing.

00:41:02.880 --> 00:41:09.640
I know most of the modern
composers do not write, they type.

00:41:09.640 --> 00:41:11.430
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: A lot of them do.

00:41:11.430 --> 00:41:14.980
Some of them still
do it the other way.

00:41:14.980 --> 00:41:18.990
&gt;&gt; Okay. But I think
for future generations

00:41:18.990 --> 00:41:24.330
and here comes the Library,
what is going to happen?

00:41:24.330 --> 00:41:25.770
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: It
is a tough question.

00:41:25.770 --> 00:41:28.240
But I would say that there
are a number of composers

00:41:28.240 --> 00:41:29.540
who do still write by hand.

00:41:29.540 --> 00:41:31.240
So we will just keep
collecting their stuff

00:41:31.240 --> 00:41:32.540
and [laughter] ignore the rest.

00:41:32.540 --> 00:41:34.200
No. I am just kidding.

00:41:34.200 --> 00:41:36.240
No. It is a tricky thing.

00:41:36.240 --> 00:41:40.240
When the Library Commissions any
composer, part of the condition

00:41:40.240 --> 00:41:43.600
of the Commission is that we
receive the original manuscript.

00:41:43.600 --> 00:41:46.240
So in the cases, and
this has been especially

00:41:46.240 --> 00:41:48.470
in the last 10 years this
has been more the case,

00:41:48.470 --> 00:41:50.980
that they have electronically
produced scores.

00:41:50.980 --> 00:41:53.590
So we try to get a
unique version of it.

00:41:53.590 --> 00:41:55.940
And the way that we handle
it is we ask for something

00:41:55.940 --> 00:41:59.490
that is before it has been
submitted to the publisher

00:41:59.490 --> 00:42:02.080
for kind of the final revisions.

00:42:02.080 --> 00:42:05.170
And sometimes composers will
give us little extra bits.

00:42:05.170 --> 00:42:09.560
They will give us further revisions
they might make after the fact.

00:42:09.560 --> 00:42:12.410
They initial each page so it, you
know there is something about it

00:42:12.410 --> 00:42:17.140
that is unique and still of use
to researchers who may have access

00:42:17.140 --> 00:42:19.830
to the published score, but
there might be something

00:42:19.830 --> 00:42:21.340
to be found in the other one.

00:42:21.340 --> 00:42:24.800 position:56%
But it is definitely an issue and
actually one of the bigger issues is

00:42:24.800 --> 00:42:28.850
for composers who have an
electroacoustic component

00:42:28.850 --> 00:42:30.150
to their work.

00:42:30.150 --> 00:42:33.860
And how does one preserve, you
know, particular technology

00:42:33.860 --> 00:42:36.900
that might be common right
now, but 20 years from now,

00:42:36.900 --> 00:42:38.950
50 years from now, it
is not going to be.

00:42:38.950 --> 00:42:45.850
So that is a challenge that
is a work in progress I think.

