00:43:52.180 --> 00:43:53.480
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Choi: Yeah.

00:43:53.480 --> 00:43:54.780
Absolutely.

00:43:54.780 --> 00:43:59.080
There is another book I was just
reading, just the other day.

00:43:59.080 --> 00:44:01.160 position:56%
The. It is called Free Improvisation

00:44:01.160 --> 00:44:04.280
by Derek Bailey, who
is just phenomenal.

00:44:04.280 --> 00:44:07.710
I am so lucky that I had
a chance to play with him

00:44:07.710 --> 00:44:10.910
in New York City before
he passed away.

00:44:10.910 --> 00:44:13.130
But he mentions that.

00:44:13.130 --> 00:44:16.730
Like in improve you want to
have the audience interact.

00:44:16.730 --> 00:44:20.040
You want to feel the
moment right there.

00:44:20.040 --> 00:44:22.270
So we cannot really predict.

00:44:22.270 --> 00:44:23.570
That is why.

00:44:23.570 --> 00:44:24.870
We started practicing today

00:44:24.870 --> 00:44:26.580
and I said you know what
let's just see what happens.

00:44:26.580 --> 00:44:28.660
Because you need that interaction.

00:44:28.660 --> 00:44:33.670
It is actually very crucial to
know what is going to play out.

00:44:33.670 --> 00:44:36.080
And we could feel it you know.

00:44:36.080 --> 00:44:40.660
But actually there is a,
there is one really good point

00:44:40.660 --> 00:44:42.950
that Derek Bailey mentions
in this book

00:44:42.950 --> 00:44:46.430
and says sometimes
you do not want to go

00:44:46.430 --> 00:44:49.330
with what the audience
necessarily wants

00:44:49.330 --> 00:44:52.260
because that might not be
the right move for the music.

00:44:52.260 --> 00:44:54.490
So there is this little
interplay and you kind of have

00:44:54.490 --> 00:44:57.300
to feel what is right
and wrong at the moment.

00:44:57.300 --> 00:44:59.830
&gt;&gt; Richard Carrick: Yeah it
seemed like Derek Bailey.

00:44:59.830 --> 00:45:01.860
In reading that book,
I got the sense

00:45:01.860 --> 00:45:05.410
that on one hand he was keenly
aware of everything around him.

00:45:05.410 --> 00:45:09.050
And on the other hand, he
had his own internal score

00:45:09.050 --> 00:45:10.910
that he was kind of creating.

00:45:10.910 --> 00:45:13.280
And that was, and that
was the tension

00:45:13.280 --> 00:45:15.500
that created all the
incredible, you know.

00:45:15.500 --> 00:45:19.740
If you ever hear him play,
I mean you were not sure

00:45:19.740 --> 00:45:21.260
if he was listening
to the other person

00:45:21.260 --> 00:45:23.010 position:56%
because he was doing his own things.

00:45:23.010 --> 00:45:25.370
Then you realize he was listening
to everything they were doing,

00:45:25.370 --> 00:45:27.890
but he was not trying to
imitate the other person.

00:45:27.890 --> 00:45:30.210
He was trying to create a richness

00:45:30.210 --> 00:45:34.770
from being unique inside
that context.

